BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:european-ai-society-fund-building-narrative-power-2026@artificialnouvea
 u.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: Building Narrative Power: EUR 2m funding and learning pro
 gramme
DESCRIPTION:The European AI & Society Fund is launching Building Narrative 
 Power\, a EUR 2 million funding and learning programme to counter Big Tech
 's dominance over how AI is understood\, and to help people and communitie
 s shape new ways of thinking and talking about the technology they want. T
 he Fund's strategy is to build the power of the public interest community 
 to shape the direction of AI in Europe\; narratives are central to creatin
 g the conditions for a greater say over how AI is adopted and used. THREE 
 THEMES where research shows the public already feels strongly: (1) DATA CE
 NTRES: as the EU aims to triple data centre numbers in the next five to se
 ven years\, pollution\, energy prices and compromised grid access have mob
 ilised communities across the political spectrum\; proposals should explor
 e narrative questions that move communities beyond resistance towards enga
 gement in shaping data centre expansion. (2) AI AND JOBS: 57% of the publi
 c in a recent study expressed concern about how AI will change employment\
 , more pronounced among lower-income people\, and the concern is not only 
 displacement but the quality and nature of work\, autonomy and dignity\; p
 roposals should move the debate from generalised anxiety into a mobilising
  issue that shapes the future of work. (3) YOUNG PEOPLE: beyond the stride
 nt social media ban debate\, young people encounter AI in education\, frie
 ndships and future careers\, and their wider views are rarely heard\; prop
 osals should build narratives that help young people shape the technologie
 s that will influence their lives. LEARNING PROGRAMME: grantees join a com
 munity of practice\, sharing experiences across issues and places\, suppor
 ting each other through delivery and reflecting on which strategies and st
 ories have most salience\, with findings feeding back to the Fund and othe
 r funders. Deadline for first-stage applications is 31 August 2026.\n\nOrg
 anisation: European AI & Society Fund\nLocation: Europe (organisations acr
 oss Europe)\nAward: Grants of up to EUR 150\,000 from a EUR 2 million prog
 ramme\, plus participation in a learning programme and community of practi
 ce. No application fee.\nDuration: Project grant with an accompanying lear
 ning programme\n\nMore: https://europeanaifund.org/newspublications/call-f
 or-proposals-new-e2m-building-narrative-power-funding-and-learning-program
 me/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://europeanaifund.org/newspublications/call-for-proposals-new-e2m-
 building-narrative-power-funding-and-learning-programme/?utm_source=artifi
 cialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Europe (organisations across Europe)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:aixdesign-kb-national-library-ai-exhibition-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: AIxDESIGN x KB: Open Call for Sessions\, (Art)works and P
 erformances
DESCRIPTION:AIxDESIGN and the KB (Koninklijke Bibliotheek\, the National Li
 brary of the Netherlands) are building an exhibition and public programme 
 about AI\, made from the national collection\, at the KB in The Hague. Nad
 ia Piet is Creative Lead with the AIxDESIGN community\, co-presented with 
 the KB. The premise: long before neural nets\, libraries were the machines
  we built to organise human knowledge\, and the show uses the KB's collect
 ion to look at what AI is\, where it comes from\, and how it connects to t
 he older story of how we store\, sort\, and search what we know. Part of t
 he show lives in the KB Atelier\, with talks\, workshops\, and screenings 
 alongside\, intended as AI literacy you can wander into. WHAT THEY WANT: w
 ork that engages AI in some way (critical\, creative\, hands-on\, or playf
 ul)\; bonus if it also speaks to archives\, libraries\, or how we store an
 d sort knowledge\, though you do not need to touch the KB's collection to 
 take part. You may pitch to more than one track: (A) SOMETHING FOR THE OPE
 NING NIGHT\, a performance\, talk\, screening\, tour\, ritual\, booth\, ga
 me\, or other experience for the November 2026 opening\, fee EUR 1\,500 to
  2\,000\; (B) A SESSION IN THE EVENTS PROGRAMME\, a workshop or other sess
 ion once during the three-month run\, around 2.5 to 4 hours\, fee EUR 2\,0
 00 to 2\,500\; (C) AN (ART)WORK FOR THE EXHIBITION\, existing work in any 
 format (installation\, sculpture\, zine stand\, a corner of your own) stur
 dy enough for a public area with daily traffic\, honorarium EUR 200 to 400
  including licensing and production\; (D) SOMETHING ELSE ENTIRELY\, pitch 
 it anyway. WHO: artists\, designers\, researchers\, technologists\, perfor
 mers\, musicians\, archivists\, or educators working around AI\, data\, li
 braries\, or cultural heritage\; no finished idea or polished CV needed\, 
 just a clear\, specific pitch. You can be based anywhere and they especial
 ly welcome people outside the Netherlands\; the show is in-person in The H
 ague and the fee stays the same wherever you are coming from. HOW TO APPLY
 : send a short pitch through the form (which track\, your idea in a paragr
 aph or two\, roughly what it would need\, and a link to your work)\; takes
  about five minutes\, no full application required. Deadline: end of Augus
 t 2026. Questions to hello@aixdesign.co.\n\nOrganisation: AIxDESIGN\, co-p
 resented with the Koninklijke Bibliotheek (KB)\, National Library of the N
 etherlands\nLocation: KB\, The Hague\, Netherlands (in-person exhibition a
 nd programme)\; pitches welcome from people based anywhere\nAward: Fees by
  track: opening-night experience EUR 1\,500 to 2\,000\; a session in the e
 vents programme EUR 2\,000 to 2\,500\; an existing (art)work for the exhib
 ition EUR 200 to 400 honorarium (including licensing and production). The 
 fee stays the same wherever you are based.\nDuration: Exhibition runs Nove
 mber 2026 to February 2027\; opening event November 2026\n\nMore: https://
 nadiapiet.notion.site/Open-Call-AIxDESIGN-x-KB-Sessions-Art-works-More-38f
 37d0038338102b128c57cbeb16d2d?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_me
 dium=referral
URL:https://nadiapiet.notion.site/Open-Call-AIxDESIGN-x-KB-Sessions-Art-wor
 ks-More-38f37d0038338102b128c57cbeb16d2d?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:KB\, The Hague\, Netherlands (in-person exhibition and programme)\
 ; pitches welcome from people based anywhere
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ddc-trygfonden-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Digital Democracy Centre x TrygFonden Fellowship Program 
 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Digital Democracy Centre (DDC) at the University of Souther
 n Denmark\, with support from TrygFonden\, is calling for applications for
  its 2027 fellowship cohort. The program fosters collaboration between res
 earchers\, journalists\, and policymakers exploring the impact of digital 
 technology and AI on media\, politics\, and democracy. Fellows collaborate
  with a self-selected DDC mentor to generate new knowledge\, contribute to
  public debate\, develop networks\, and produce tangible outreach outputs 
 such as policy briefs\, educational packages\, and talks. THREE FELLOWSHIP
  TYPES: (1) academic fellows researching digital technologies and democrac
 y\; (2) journalist fellows covering digital technology and democracy\; (3)
  policy fellows contributing to the regulatory debate. Target group: resea
 rchers\, journalism graduates\, and policymakers in research/educational i
 nstitutions\, media organizations\, ministries\, NGOs\, etc. PRIORITIES: p
 rojects with clear relevance to Denmark or Danish society (including compa
 rative/international projects yielding insights relevant to a Danish conte
 xt)\; in 2027\, projects related to DDC's Hybrid Warfare Initiative (socie
 tal resilience to new forms of international conflict\, with a focus on di
 gital technologies and AI) are also prioritized. EXPECTATIONS: applicants 
 must secure confirmation of mentorship from their desired DDC mentor BEFOR
 E applying (applications without a confirmed mentor are automatically reje
 cted\; PhD students and research assistants are generally not eligible as 
 mentors\, and Sten Schaumburg-Muller is unavailable as a mentor for the 20
 27 call)\; applicants must also coordinate support from their current supe
 rvisors/managers. Fellows engage in DDC activities\, seminars/workshops\, 
 and public outreach\, and submit a short report within two months of finis
 hing. APPLICATION (in English): preliminary project title\, fellowship typ
 e\, brief project description (max 1000 chars)\, detailed description and 
 timeline (max 2400 chars\, including duration\, confirmed mentor\, and rem
 ote/in-office work plan)\, description of activities and collaboration wit
 h external practice partners (max 1000 chars)\, expected product/impact/ou
 tput (max 500 chars)\, a CV (max 5 pages)\, and an overview of the posts f
 or which financial support is sought. Submit the application form (PDF or 
 Word) plus CV as PDFs to ddc@sdu.dk with subject line 'DDC / TrygFonden Fe
 llowship application'. Deadline 1 September 2026\; decisions communicated 
 no later than 1 October 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Digital Democracy Centre (U
 niversity of Southern Denmark)\, with support from TrygFonden\nLocation: O
 dense\, Denmark (University of Southern Denmark). Flexible mix of in-offic
 e stays at the DDC in Odense and remote periods\; stays planned to the Dan
 ish working calendar.\nAward: Either a salary subsidy or a stipend to help
  with travel and/or housing\; specific benefits (financial support\, acces
 s to DDC research resources\, flexible working spaces\, speaker series\, n
 etworks) vary by agreement between the fellow\, DDC\, and partnering organ
 izations. Applicants describe the posts they seek support for (flights\, h
 ousing\, research costs\, salary compensation\, stipend\, etc.).\nDuration
 : Flexible\; typically 2-6 months (minimum two months\, can include shorte
 r DDC stays and remote periods)\, longer in exceptional cases. Fellowships
  start anywhere in 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.sdu.dk/en/forskning/forsknin
 gsenheder/samf/digitaldemocracycentre/news+folder/ddcxtrygfonden-fellowshi
 p-call-2027?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.sdu.dk/en/forskning/forskningsenheder/samf/digitaldemocracy
 centre/news+folder/ddcxtrygfonden-fellowship-call-2027?utm_source=artifici
 alnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Odense\, Denmark (University of Southern Denmark). Flexible mix of
  in-office stays at the DDC in Odense and remote periods\; stays planned t
 o the Danish working calendar.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:musikfonds-stip-6-ai-scholarship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Musikfonds: STIP-6 AI Scholarship Programme 2027 (Germany
 )
DESCRIPTION:STIP-6 is a Musikfonds scholarship programme supporting profess
 ional musicians who work on AI-based composition and who reflect criticall
 y and societally on the role of artificial intelligence in music. Ten scho
 larships of EUR 30\,000 each are awarded for the 2027 working year. Open t
 o Germany-based professional freelance musicians across genres\; no comput
 er-science or technical background is required. Deadline 30 June 2026\, 18
 :00 CET. Details and application via the Musikfonds funding programmes pag
 e (apply at musikfonds-antrag.de). NOTE: this entry was sourced from resea
 rch and the funder's pages may update\; confirm current figures and deadli
 ne before applying.\n\nOrganisation: musikfonds e.V.\nLocation: Germany. O
 pen to Germany-based professional freelance musicians\; no computer-scienc
 e background required.\nAward: EUR 30\,000 lump sum per scholarship\, paid
  in twelve monthly installments across January to December 2027. Ten schol
 arships available. No application fee.\nDuration: Twelve months (January t
 o December 2027).\n\nMore: https://www.musikfonds.de/foerderprogramme?utm_
 source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.musikfonds.de/foerderprogramme?utm_source=artificialnouveau
 grantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Germany. Open to Germany-based professional freelance musicians\; 
 no computer-science background required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:onassis-onx-summer-school-innovation-tech-culture-2026@artificialnouvea
 u.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260621
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260622
SUMMARY:Deadline: Onassis ONX & ACE: Summer School 2026\, Innovation\, Tech
  & Culture (Worldbuilding)
DESCRIPTION:The Summer School: Innovation\, Tech & Culture\, organised by O
 nassis ONX and ACE for a third consecutive year\, invites creative profess
 ionals and teams to explore the convergence of art\, technology and sustai
 nable entrepreneurship\, bridging Culture and Digital Arts with Technology
 \, Artificial Intelligence and Entrepreneurship. The 2026 edition is again
  dedicated to 'Worldbuilding'\, a methodology that fuels innovation and fo
 sters novel entrepreneurial models: the emphasis shifts from the project o
 r end product to the narratives that frame and sustain them\, building imm
 ersive worlds around products and turning the audience into co-shapers of 
 the experience. The program challenges traditional product design and prom
 otion practices by harnessing new technologies\, art thinking and innovati
 ve design. SYLLABUS: Media & Art History\; Speculative & Interactive Desig
 n Theory\; Ethics\, Art & Technology\; Computational Creativity\; AI-enabl
 ed Tech Development\; Innovation & Entrepreneurship (business modeling and
  product validation)\; building for speed with venture capital backing\; u
 nderstanding the market and audience\; branding\, marketing and digital ch
 annels\; and IP management\, licensing and contracts. Participants attend 
 lectures and receive mentorship from keynote speakers of AUEB\, the NYU Ta
 ndon School of Engineering and Onassis ONX Fellows\, plus talks by leading
  international professionals such as artist-technologists Jiabao Li and Co
 oper Galvin. OPPORTUNITIES: access to funding opportunities and an incubat
 ion program for selected teams after completion\; development of entrepren
 eurial\, artistic and technological skills\; and networking and growth opp
 ortunities for participating companies. WHO CAN APPLY: undergraduate and p
 ostgraduate students and early-career professionals\; established professi
 onals and corporate employees in arts\, culture\, design\, marketing\, tec
 hnology and business administration. PARTICIPATION: individual application
 \, or as a member of a corporate team or company representative\; in-perso
 n attendance required\; working language English\; up to 30 participants. 
 NOTE: this is a free educational program rather than a paid grant\; no par
 ticipation or application fee. Apply via the Onassis Directory by 21 June 
 2026. Inquiries: digital@onassis.org.\n\nOrganisation: Onassis ONX\, in co
 llaboration with ACE (Athens Center for Entrepreneurship & Innovation\, AU
 EB) and NYU Tandon School of Engineering\nLocation: Athens\, Greece (Athen
 s University of Economics and Business)\; in-person attendance required.\n
 Award: Free educational program (NO participation fee and no application f
 ee)\, not a paid grant: there is no stipend\, and travel and accommodation
  are not mentioned as covered. BENEFITS: lectures and mentorship from inte
 rnationally recognised artists\, designers\, entrepreneurs and tech profes
 sionals (AUEB\, NYU Tandon\, and Onassis ONX Fellows in Athens and New Yor
 k)\; access to funding opportunities and an incubation program for selecte
 d teams after completion\; exposure to cutting-edge digital tools and inte
 rdisciplinary collaboration\; and networking. Limited to 30 participants.\
 nDuration: Two weeks\, 1 to 13 July 2026\n\nMore: https://www.onassis.org/
 open-calls-past/open-call-summer-school-2026-innovation-tech-culture?utm_s
 ource=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.onassis.org/open-calls-past/open-call-summer-school-2026-in
 novation-tech-culture?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=ref
 erral
LOCATION:Athens\, Greece (Athens University of Economics and Business)\; in
 -person attendance required.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:prototype-fund-switzerland-responsible-sustainable-ai-2026-27@artificia
 lnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260907
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260908
SUMMARY:Deadline: Prototype Fund Switzerland 2026-27: Responsible and Susta
 inable AI
DESCRIPTION:Since 2020 the Prototype Fund Switzerland has strengthened the 
 common good with open-source\, public-interest technology\, supporting int
 erdisciplinary teams to develop and test early-stage projects that show ho
 w open source\, data and digital technologies such as AI can create real s
 ocietal value. The 2026-2027 edition focuses on Responsible and Sustainabl
 e AI: building the path toward a more responsible and sustainable AI\, tec
 h and digitalization landscape\, open source and beyond. THIS YEAR'S FOCUS
 : projects that reduce resource use\, energy consumption or emissions\; st
 rengthen accountability\, transparency and governance\; and contribute to 
 resilient and trustworthy digital systems\, including sustainable digitali
 zation and digital sufficiency\, public-interest AI and data infrastructur
 es\, and tools for governance\, oversight or digital sovereignty. PUBLIC I
 NTEREST TECH areas span sustainability and climate\, participation and civ
 ic tech\, education and literacy\, health and inclusion\, and open knowled
 ge and data. WHO THEY FUND: individuals and small teams open to open sourc
 e\, AI and iterative experimentation\, eager to combine technical capabili
 ty with societal and political awareness\, willing to share learnings\, mo
 tivated to work on pressing societal problems through technology\, with an
  early-stage but well-thought-out concept\, and eligible to work in Switze
 rland. SUPPORT: up to CHF 50\,000 in funding\, a 4-month prototyping phase
 \, coaching\, mentoring and workshops\, and access to a strong network acr
 oss tech\, policy and society. Teams are strongly encouraged (though not r
 equired) to publish code\, data or components under open-source licenses a
 nd to document their approach. TIMELINE: applications 21 July to 7 Septemb
 er 2026\; rolling jury selection August-September 2026\; prototyping mid-O
 ctober 2026 to mid-February 2027\; outputs and learnings November 2026 to 
 July 2027. Questions: info@prototypefund.ch.\n\nOrganisation: Prototype Fu
 nd Switzerland (Opendata.ch)\nLocation: Switzerland\; applicants must be e
 ligible to work in Switzerland.\nAward: Up to CHF 50\,000 per project\, pl
 us coaching\, mentoring and workshops and access to a tech/policy/society 
 network. No application fee.\nDuration: 4-month prototyping phase (mid-Oct
 ober 2026 to mid-February 2027)\n\nMore: https://prototypefund.opendata.ch
 /en/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://prototypefund.opendata.ch/en/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Switzerland\; applicants must be eligible to work in Switzerland.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:coe-democracy-hackathon-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260605
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260606
SUMMARY:Deadline: Council of Europe: New Democratic Pact for Europe Democra
 cy Hackathon 2026 (Strasbourg)
DESCRIPTION:Council of Europe civic-tech hackathon to combat online hate sp
 eech and develop tech solutions for democracy\, run alongside No Hate Spee
 ch Week and backed by a Microsoft prize pool. Four challenge tracks cover 
 privacy-preserving hate speech detection\, identifying coordinated inauthe
 ntic behaviour\, gender-based violence reporting systems\, and innovative 
 social transformation approaches. ELIGIBILITY: pre-formed multidisciplinar
 y teams of 3-4 (typically a technologist/developer\, a democracy or policy
  expert\, and a designer or UX innovator)\; residents of the 46 Council of
  Europe member states\; coding experience is not required for every team m
 ember. FORMAT: four online warm-up sessions\, then a three-day in-person f
 inale at the Palais de l'Europe\, Strasbourg\, 17-19 June 2026.\n\nOrganis
 ation: Council of Europe (under the Monaco Presidency of the Committee of 
 Ministers)\, in partnership with No Hate Speech Week and Microsoft\nLocati
 on: Palais de l'Europe\, Strasbourg\, France (hybrid: four online warm-up 
 sessions leading to a three-day in-person finale)\nAward: EUR 50\,000 Micr
 osoft-funded prize pool distributed among winning teams. Travel and accomm
 odation covered for the 20 selected finalist teams. No application fee.\nD
 uration: Online warm-up sessions plus three-day in-person hackathon (17-19
  June 2026)\n\nMore: https://democracyhackathon.coe.int/?utm_source=artifi
 cialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://democracyhackathon.coe.int/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantde
 sk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Palais de l'Europe\, Strasbourg\, France (hybrid: four online warm
 -up sessions leading to a three-day in-person finale)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:talos-ai-policy-leaders-programme-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T114943Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260614
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:Deadline: Talos Network: AI Policy Leaders Programme 2026 (Autumn c
 ohort)
DESCRIPTION:The Talos Network's Policy Leaders Programme is built for exper
 ienced professionals ready to move into shaping European governance of adv
 anced AI. It runs a part-time virtual European AI Policy Bootcamp (10 Sep 
 - 22 Oct 2026\, weekly Thursday calls\, ~10 hrs/week\, designed around a f
 ull-time job) with a fully-reimbursed week-long policymaking summit in Bru
 ssels (3-9 Oct 2026)\, and a Placement track offering a 12-month paid plac
 ement at a relevant AI-focused organisation (base EUR 5\,000/month for Bru
 ssels). Fellows get intensive 1-1 mentoring and career coaching\, access t
 o the Talos Network and alumni\, a curated senior peer cohort\, and tailor
 ed financial support. ELIGIBILITY: experienced professionals (around 8-10+
  years) in high-stakes environments such as government\, international org
 anisations\, think tanks\, industry or academia\, with a track record of i
 nfluencing senior decision-makers\, looking to transition into AI governan
 ce or strengthen the AI dimension of their existing work\; Europe-focused.
  Application deadline 14 June 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Talos Network\nLocati
 on: Europe (virtual bootcamp + week-long Brussels summit\; placements in B
 russels or other European cities)\nAward: Placement track: a 12-month paid
  placement at an AI-focused organisation\, base EUR 5\,000/month for Bruss
 els (adjusted for cost of living elsewhere). Plus a fully-reimbursed 6-day
  Brussels policymaking summit\, tailored financial support (coworking\, co
 nference attendance\, career-transition funding)\, and intensive 1-1 mento
 ring. No application fee.\nDuration: Virtual bootcamp 10 Sep - 22 Oct 2026
  (approx. 10 hrs/week) plus a 12-month paid placement (placement track)\n\
 nMore: https://www.talosnetwork.org/policy-leaders-programme?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.talosnetwork.org/policy-leaders-programme?utm_source=artifi
 cialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Europe (virtual bootcamp + week-long Brussels summit\; placements 
 in Brussels or other European cities)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
